---
import Layout from "$components/layout.astro";

import "$styles/pages/about.css";

const links = {
  htmx: "https://htmx.org",
  alpine: "https://alpinejs.dev",
  svelte: "https://svelte.dev",
  astro: "https://astro.build",
  d1: "https://www.cloudflare.com/en-gb/developer-platform/products/d1/",
  emailService: "https://developers.cloudflare.com/email-service/",
  emailRouting: "https://www.cloudflare.com/en-gb/developer-platform/products/email-routing/",
  hono: "https://hono.dev",
  resend: "https://resend.dev/",
  drizzle: "https://orm.drizzle.team",
  workers: "https://www.cloudflare.com/en-gb/developer-platform/products/workers/",
  workersOG: "https://npmx.dev/package/workers-og",
  satori: "https://github.com/vercel/satori",
};

const projects = [
  {
    name: "tilt-svelte",
    description:
      "a smooth 3D tilt effect as a Svelte 5 attachment, with glare, scale, and programmatic control.",
    href: "https://savy011.github.io/tilt-svelte",
  },
  {
    name: "Rubble",
    description: "an archive for weeekly's bubble chats.",
    href: "https://rubble.yvas.me",
  },
  {
    name: "Weeekly Weverse Archive",
    description: "an archive of Weeekly's Weverse posts.",
    href: "https://weeekly-weverse.yvas.me",
  },
];
---

<Layout title="about - ama.yvas.me">
  <Fragment slot="head-content">
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="the why and the stack"
    />
    <meta
      property="og:image"
      content={new URL("/about/og.png", Astro.site).href}
    />
    <meta
      name="twitter:image"
      content={new URL("/about/og.png", Astro.site).href}
    />
  </Fragment>

  <h1>about<br /><span>this site.</span></h1>

  <section>
    <div>
      <h2>why does this exist?</h2>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p>
        Mostly because I was bored, and wanted a smol project to work on. And I've heard about htmx,
        ever since i got into web-dev, so I wanted to try it out, or atleast get a feel of it.
      </p>
      <br />
      <p>
        Daniel Roe made an
        <a href="https://roe.dev/ama">ama page</a>
        on his website and I thought, "hey maybe i can try this out too".
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div>
      <h2>what does this use? (aka the stack)</h2>
    </div>
    <div>
      <p>
        The form is really the only thing which needed some js (cause of turnstile), so I ended up
        using <a href={links.alpine}>alpine.js</a> and <a href={links.htmx}>htmx</a> and
        <a href={links.astro}>astro</a>
        instead of my usual pick,
        <a href={links.svelte}>sveltekit</a>.
      </p>
      <br />
      <p>
        All question are saved to a <a href={links.d1}>cloudflare D1</a> database, and I use
        <a href={links.drizzle}>drizzle</a>
        as my orm. After a question is added to the database, an email with the question as the body
        is sent to my email. I originally used
        <a href={links.emailService}>cloudflare email</a>
        sending to send them, but I later realized it is paid, so I switched it with
        <a href={links.resend}>resend</a>. Answering to a question is just as easy as replying to
        the email, which is handled by a cloudflare worker with
        <a href={links.emailRouting}>email routing.</a>
      </p>
      <br />
      <p>
        This saved me the hassle of creating a whole different frontend for answering the question,
        and replying to emails is just simply easy.
      </p>
      <p>
        The OG Images are generated with <a href={links.satori}>satori</a> and resvg. Using them in
        a worker is quite a setup, so I opted to use a <a href={links.workersOG}>library</a> to do
        the heavy work for me.
      </p>
      <br />
      <p>
        I setup some API endpoints too, which are mounted on a
        <a href={links.hono}>Hono</a>
        instance.
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li class="link">/ask</li>
        <li class="link">/questions</li>
        <li class="link">/questions/:id</li>
      </ul>
      <br />
      <p>
        oh yea, And the app is deployed on <a href={links.workers}>cloudflare workers</a> as well.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section>
    <div>
      <h2>some other projects by me</h2>
    </div>
    <div>
      <ul>
        {projects.map(p => (
              <li><a href={p.href}>{p.name}</a>: {p.description}</li>
              ))}
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
